In [mathematics](/Mathematics), specifically within the realm of [group theory](/Group_theory), a [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) isn't some esoteric construct for the initiated. It is, quite simply, the [group](/Group_(mathematics)) that describes all the [symmetries](/Symmetry) of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) — an object whose sides and angles are all equal. This includes not only the obvious [rotations](/Rotational_symmetry) but also the more subtle [reflections](/Reflection_symmetry). These groups, despite their apparent simplicity, are rather foundational. They represent some of the most straightforward examples of [finite groups](/Finite_group) and, as such, are surprisingly prevalent in various fields, from pure [group theory](/Group_theory) and [geometry](/Geometry) to the more applied domain of [chemistry](/Chemistry). One might even say they're inescapable, like a bad habit.

Now, because nothing in mathematics can ever be entirely straightforward, the notation used to denote these [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) inconveniently varies between [geometry](/Geometry) and [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra). In [geometry](/Geometry), one typically encounters D n or Dih n when referring to the [symmetries](/Symmetry) of an n -gon, which, to be clear, is a group of order 2 n . However, in the more abstract corners of [algebra](/Abstract_algebra), the very same group is often denoted D 2 n . This article, in a concession to geometric clarity, will adhere to the geometric convention of D n . Let's not make things more complicated than they already are.

### Definition

The term "dihedral" itself is derived from the Greek elements "di-" (meaning "two") and "-hedron" (from *hédra*, meaning "face of a geometrical solid"). So, literally, it refers to something with "two faces." In the context of polygons, this implies the two distinct surfaces of the shape, or more accurately, the two sides from which one might view its symmetries.

#### Elements

Consider a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) with $n$ sides. One might assume its [symmetries](/Symmetry) are straightforward, but they are more numerous than a casual glance suggests. Such a polygon possesses precisely $2n$ distinct [symmetries](/Symmetry), assuming, of course, that $n \geq 3$. These comprise $n$ [rotational symmetries](/Rotational_symmetry) and an equal number of $n$ [reflection symmetries](/Reflection_symmetry). These specific [rotations](/Rotation) and [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) are the very elements that constitute the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) denoted as ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$.

The nature of these [reflection symmetries](/Reflection_symmetry) slightly shifts depending on the parity of $n$. If $n$ is an odd number, each axis of symmetry elegantly bisects one side and simultaneously passes through the opposite vertex. It's a rather neat arrangement. If, however, $n$ is even, the axes of symmetry diverge into two distinct types: there are $n/2$ axes that connect the midpoints of opposing sides, and another $n/2$ axes that pass directly through opposite vertices. Regardless of $n$'s parity, the total count remains $n$ axes of symmetry, always leading to $2n$ elements within the full [symmetry group](/Symmetry_group). A rather crucial property to note is that performing one [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) about an axis of symmetry, and then immediately following it with another [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) about a different axis, invariably results in a [rotation](/Rotation). The angle of this resultant [rotation](/Rotation) will always be exactly twice the angle separating the two initial reflection axes.

To illustrate this concept, one might consider the familiar [stop sign](/Stop_sign), which, mathematically speaking, is a regular octagon. The image provided demonstrates the profound effect of the sixteen elements that make up ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{8}}$ on such an object. The first row meticulously displays the outcome of the eight distinct [rotations](/Rotation), while the second row showcases the consequence of the eight [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)). Each operation begins with the stop sign oriented exactly as it appears in the top-left corner, emphasizing the transformative power of these group elements.

### Group structure

As is the case with any well-behaved [geometric object](/Geometry), the [composition](/Composition_of_functions) of any two [symmetries](/Symmetry) of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) will, without fail, yield yet another [symmetry](/Symmetry) of that very same object. This inherent closure, when combined with the operation of composing [symmetries](/Symmetry) to produce new ones, bestows upon the [symmetries](/Symmetry) of a polygon the elegant [algebraic structure](/Algebraic_structure) of a [finite group](/Finite_group). It's almost as if they were designed for it.

Crucially, when considering the [composition](/Composition_of_functions) of [symmetries](/Symmetry), it's important to understand that the lines of reflection, typically labeled S 0 , S 1 , and S 2 in illustrative examples, are fixed in space. They do not shift or move as the [symmetry operation](/Symmetry) (be it a [rotation](/Rotation) or a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics))) is applied to the polygon itself. This distinction becomes paramount when one attempts to perform successive [compositions](/Composition_of_functions) of [symmetries](/Symmetry), ensuring that the underlying reference frame remains consistent.

The subsequent [Cayley table](/Cayley_table) serves as an explicit demonstration of the effect of [composition](/Composition_of_functions) within the [dihedral group of order 6](/Dihedral_group_of_order_6), more commonly known as ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{3}}$ — which, for the uninitiated, represents the [symmetries](/Symmetry) of an [equilateral triangle](/Equilateral_triangle). Here, the element ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{0}}$ represents the [identity](/Identity_element), meaning no change at all. ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{1}}$ and ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{2}}$ denote precise counterclockwise [rotations](/Rotation) of 120° and 240°, respectively. The elements ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{0}}$, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{1}}$, and ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{2}}$ correspond to [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across the three distinct lines of symmetry, as depicted in the accompanying visual aid.

| | r0 | r1 | r2 | s0 | s1 | s2 |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| r0 | r0 | r1 | r2 | s0 | s1 | s2 |
| r1 | r1 | r2 | r0 | s1 | s2 | s0 |
| r2 | r2 | r0 | r1 | s2 | s0 | s1 |
| s0 | s0 | s2 | s1 | r0 | r2 | r1 |
| s1 | s1 | s0 | s2 | r1 | r0 | r2 |
| s2 | s2 | s1 | s0 | r2 | r1 | r0 |

For example, observe the entry ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{2}\mathrm {s} _{1}=\mathrm {r} _{1}}$. This is not merely an arbitrary assignment but a concrete result: performing the [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{1}}$ first, and then applying the [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{2}}$, is mathematically equivalent to a single [rotation](/Rotation) of 120°. A crucial, if sometimes overlooked, convention is that the order of elements in these [composition](/Composition_of_functions) operations proceeds from right to left. This reflects the standard mathematical convention where an element is understood to act upon the expression immediately to its right. Furthermore, it quickly becomes apparent that this [composition](/Composition_of_functions) operation is decidedly not [commutative](/Commutativity). That is, the order in which you apply these [symmetries](/Symmetry) fundamentally matters, a property that distinguishes non-[abelian groups](/Abelian_group).

More generally, the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ is composed of elements typically designated as ${\displaystyle r_{0},\dots ,r_{n-1}}$ (representing [rotations](/Rotation)) and ${\displaystyle s_{0},\dots ,s_{n-1}}$ (representing [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics))). Their [composition](/Composition_of_functions) is governed by a set of well-defined formulae:

${\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\mathrm {r} _{i}\,\mathrm {r} _{j}=\mathrm {r} _{i+j},&\qquad \mathrm {r} _{i}\,\mathrm {s} _{j}=\mathrm {s} _{i+j},\\\mathrm {s} _{i}\,\mathrm {r} _{j}=\mathrm {s} _{i-j},&\qquad \mathrm {s} _{i}\,\mathrm {s} _{j}=\mathrm {r} _{i-j}.\end{aligned}}}$

It is imperative to note that in all these operations, the addition and subtraction of the subscripts ($i$ and $j$) are performed using [modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic) with a modulus of $n$. This ensures that the resulting subscript always falls within the valid range of 0 to $n-1$, effectively wrapping around the polygon's sides.

### Matrix representation

For those who appreciate precision and a more concrete visualization, [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) offer a rather elegant [matrix representation](/Matrix_(mathematics)). By centering the [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) precisely at the [origin](/Origin_(mathematics)) of a [Cartesian coordinate system](/Cartesian_coordinate_system), the elements of the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) can be understood as [linear transformations](/Linear_map) of the [plane](/Cartesian_coordinate_system). This allows each element of ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ to be represented by a [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)), where the [composition](/Composition_of_functions) of [symmetries](/Symmetry) translates directly into [matrix multiplication](/Matrix_multiplication). This is a quintessential example of a two-dimensional [group representation](/Group_representation), providing a powerful tool for analyzing the group's actions.

Consider, for instance, the elements of the [dihedral group of order 8](/Dihedral_group_of_order_8), denoted as ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{4}}$ — which, as you might recall, is the [group symmetry](/Symmetry_group) of a [square](/Square). These eight distinct elements can be represented by the following eight [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)), offering a clear algebraic mapping of their geometric actions:

${\displaystyle {\begin{matrix}\mathrm {r} _{0}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}1&0\\[0.2em]0&1\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {r} _{1}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}0&-1\\[0.2em]1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {r} _{2}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}-1&0\\[0.2em]0&-1\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {r} _{3}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}0&1\\[0.2em]-1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right),\\[1em]\mathrm {s} _{0}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}1&0\\[0.2em]0&-1\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {s} _{1}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}0&1\\[0.2em]1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {s} _{2}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}-1&0\\[0.2em]0&1\end{smallmatrix}}\right),&\mathrm {s} _{3}=\left({\begin{smallmatrix}0&-1\\[0.2em]-1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right).\end{matrix}}}$

In this specific arrangement, these [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)) effectively [represent](/Group_representation) the [symmetries](/Symmetry) of a [square](/Square) that is both axis-aligned and centered at the [origin](/Origin_(mathematics)). They operate on the plane through multiplication with [column vectors](/Column_vector) of coordinates, typically expressed as ${\textstyle {\bigl (}{\begin{smallmatrix}x\\y\end{smallmatrix}}{\bigr )}}$. The matrix ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{0}}$ is the [identity element](/Identity_element), leaving the square unchanged. The matrices ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{0}}$ and ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{2}}$ correspond to [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across the horizontal and vertical axes, respectively. Meanwhile, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{1}}$ and ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{3}}$ represent [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across the main diagonals of the square. The remaining elements, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{1}}$, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{2}}$, and ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{3}}$, are the distinct [rotations](/Rotation_(mathematics)) around the center, moving the square without flipping it.

| r0 | r1 | r2 | r3 |
|---|---|---|---|
| The square's initial position | Rotation by 270° | Rotation by 180° | Rotation by 90° anticlockwise |

| s0 | s1 | s2 | s3 |
|---|---|---|---|
| Horizontal reflection | Vertical reflection | Diagonal NW–SE reflection | Diagonal NE–SW reflection |

In a more general formulation, the [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)) corresponding to the elements of the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ take on the following elegant, trigonometric form:

${\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\mathrm {r} _{k}&={\begin{pmatrix}\cos {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}&-\sin {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}\\\sin {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}&\cos {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}\end{pmatrix}}\ \ {\text{and}}\\[5pt]\mathrm {s} _{k}&={\begin{pmatrix}\cos {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}&\sin {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}\\\sin {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}&-\cos {\frac {2\pi k}{n}}\end{pmatrix}}.\end{aligned}}}$

Here, the element ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{k}}$ is a classic [rotation matrix](/Rotation_matrix), meticulously expressing a counterclockwise [rotation](/Rotation_(mathematics)) by an angle of ${\displaystyle 2\pi k/n}$ radians. Conversely, the element ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{k}}$ represents a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across a line that forms an angle of ${\displaystyle \pi k/n}$ radians with the positive $x$-axis. These generalized forms are crucial for understanding how [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) scale and behave for any regular $n$-gon.

### Other definitions

For those who appreciate a more abstract, structural perspective, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ can be precisely defined as the [semidirect product](/Semidirect_product) of the cyclic group ${\displaystyle \mathrm {C} _{2}=\{1,s\}}$ acting upon the cyclic group ${\displaystyle \mathrm {C} _{n}}$. This action is achieved through the automorphism ${\displaystyle \varphi _{s}(r)=r^{-1}}$, which essentially means that the reflection element $s$ inverts the rotational element $r$.

Consequently, this structure leads to the following standard [presentation](/Presentation_of_a_group) for ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$:

${\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\mathrm {D} _{n}&=\left\langle r,s\mid \operatorname {ord} (r)=n,\operatorname {ord} (s)=2,srs^{-1}=r^{-1}\right\rangle \\&=\left\langle r,s\mid \operatorname {ord} (r)=n,\operatorname {ord} (s)=2,srs=r^{-1}\right\rangle \\&=\left\langle r,s\mid r^{n}=s^{2}=(sr)^{2}=1\right\rangle .\end{aligned}}}$

Here, $r$ represents a generator for the [rotational symmetries](/Rotational_symmetry) (an element of [order](/Order_(group_theory)) $n$), and $s$ represents a generator for a [reflection symmetry](/Reflection_symmetry) (an element of [order](/Order_(group_theory)) 2). The relation ${\displaystyle srs^{-1}=r^{-1}}$ (or equivalently, ${\displaystyle srs=r^{-1}}$ since $s^{-1}=s$) captures the interaction between these two types of [symmetries](/Symmetry): a reflection followed by a rotation followed by another reflection is equivalent to the inverse of the original rotation. The final line, ${\displaystyle r^{n}=s^{2}=(sr)^{2}=1}$, provides a concise set of defining relations, stating that $n$ rotations return to identity, two reflections return to identity, and a rotation followed by a reflection, then by another rotation, also results in identity.

Utilizing the relation ${\displaystyle s^{2}=1}$, which implies $s = s^{-1}$, we can also derive the relationship ${\displaystyle r=s\cdot sr}$. This implies that ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ can also be generated by two elements $s$ and $t:=sr$. This substitution then reveals an alternative, equally valid [presentation](/Presentation_of_a_group) for ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$:

${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}=\left\langle s,t\mid s^{2}=1,t^{2}=1,(st)^{n}=1\right\rangle .}$

This particular form is rather significant, as it highlights that ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ inherently belongs to the class of [Coxeter groups](/Coxeter_group). These groups are defined by generators and relations where all relations are of the form $(g_i g_j)^{k_{ij}}=1$, which makes them a fundamental object of study in geometric group theory.

### Small dihedral groups

When discussing [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group), it's customary to start with $n \geq 3$ for polygons. However, the definitions can be extended to smaller values, though they become somewhat "degenerate" and exhibit unique characteristics.

