An example illustrating subgroups derived from a hexagonal [dihedral symmetry](/Dihedral_group#Dihedral_group_as_symmetry_group_in_2D_and_rotation_group_in_3D) might be useful here, but the diagram is omitted from the original.

Let's examine the "small" cases, which are, frankly, a bit peculiar:

*   [D 1](/Dihedral_group) is [isomorphic](/Isomorphic) to [Z 2](/Cyclic_group), the [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group) of order 2. This represents the symmetries of a "1-gon" – essentially a line segment, which has one rotation (the identity) and one reflection. Not terribly exciting, but mathematically consistent.
*   [D 2](/Dihedral_group) is [isomorphic](/Isomorphic) to [K 4](/Klein_four-group), the [Klein four-group](/Klein_four-group). This corresponds to the symmetries of a "2-gon" or a line segment, with two rotations (0° and 180°) and two reflections. It's the smallest non-cyclic group, and quite distinct from its higher-order siblings.

These two small [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) are exceptional, standing apart from the others in a few key ways:

*   [D 1](/Dihedral_group) and [D 2](/Dihedral_group) are the *only* [abelian](/Abelian_group) [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group). For any $n \geq 3$, the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ is decidedly non-[abelian](/Abelian_group), meaning the order of operations matters. This is a fundamental distinction.
*   For $n \geq 3$, ${\displaystyle \mathrm {D} _{n}}$ is a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of the [symmetric group](/Symmetric_group) [S n](/Symmetric_group). However, for $n=1$ or $n=2$, this relationship breaks down. The order of [D n](/Dihedral_group) (which is $2n$) is greater than $n!$ for these values ($2 \times 1 = 2 > 1! = 1$ for $n=1$, and $2 \times 2 = 4 > 2! = 2$ for $n=2$). Therefore, [D n](/Dihedral_group) is simply too large to be a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of [S n](/Symmetric_group) in these specific instances.
*   The [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism) of [D 2](/Dihedral_group) is trivial, meaning it contains only the [identity automorphism](/Automorphism_group). For all other even values of $n$, this [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism) is isomorphic to [D n / Z 2](/Quotient_group). This subtle point reveals how [D 2](/Dihedral_group) behaves differently in terms of its internal structure.

The visual representations known as [cycle graphs](/Cycle_graph_(group)) for [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) present a rather consistent pattern. They are characterized by an $n$-element cycle, which embodies the [rotational symmetries](/Rotational_symmetry), and $n$ distinct 2-element cycles, which represent the individual [reflection symmetries](/Reflection_symmetry). In these graphs, the darkened vertex invariably denotes the [identity element](/Identity_element) of the group, with all other vertices corresponding to the remaining elements. Each cycle is formed by the successive powers of any element connected directly to the [identity element](/Identity_element), offering a clear diagrammatic representation of the group's structure.

### The dihedral group as symmetry group in 2D and rotation group in 3D

The abstract [group D n](/Dihedral_group), in its most intuitive and commonly visualized form, manifests as the [group](/Group_(mathematics)) of [Euclidean plane isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry) that maintain a fixed origin. These groups are not merely theoretical constructs; they form one of the two fundamental series of discrete [point groups in two dimensions](/Point_groups_in_two_dimensions). Specifically, [D n](/Dihedral_group) encompasses $n$ distinct [rotations](/Rotation), each a multiple of $360^\circ/n$ around the central origin. Additionally, it includes $n$ distinct [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across lines that all pass through the origin, with these lines making angles that are multiples of $180^\circ/n$ with respect to each other. This collection of operations precisely defines the [symmetry group](/Symmetry_group) of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) with $n$ sides. While this is most commonly considered for $n \geq 3$, the concept extends, albeit with some degeneracy, to the cases where $n=1$ (a plane with a single point offset from the "center" of a "1-gon") and $n=2$ (a "2-gon" or line segment).

Formally, [D n](/Dihedral_group) is elegantly [generated](/Generating_set_of_a_group) by a [rotation](/Rotation) $r$ of [order](/Order_(group_theory)) $n$ and a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) $s$ of [order](/Order_(group_theory)) 2. These two generators are linked by a crucial relation:

${\displaystyle \mathrm {srs} =\mathrm {r} ^{-1}\,}$

Geometrically, this relation is rather profound and intuitive: when you observe a [rotation](/Rotation) through a mirror (a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics))), what you perceive is an inverse [rotation](/Rotation). The direction of rotation is reversed.

In the language of [complex numbers](/Complex_numbers), this translates to multiplication by ${\displaystyle e^{2\pi i \over n}}$ for the [rotation](/Rotation) and [complex conjugation](/Complex_conjugation) for the [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)). This offers an alternative, yet equally valid, perspective on the group's operations.

When expressed in [matrix form](/Matrix_(mathematics)), we can define the fundamental rotation and reflection as:

${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{1}={\begin{bmatrix}\cos {2\pi \over n}&-\sin {2\pi \over n}\\[4pt]\sin {2\pi \over n}&\cos {2\pi \over n}\end{bmatrix}}\qquad \mathrm {s} _{0}={\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&-1\end{bmatrix}}}$

From these base elements, we can then define all other [rotations](/Rotation) as ${\displaystyle \mathrm {r} _{j}=\mathrm {r} _{1}^{j}}$ and all other [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) as ${\displaystyle \mathrm {s} _{j}=\mathrm {r} _{j}\,\mathrm {s} _{0}}$ for ${\displaystyle j\in \{1,\ldots ,n-1\}}$. With these definitions in place, the product rules for [D n](/Dihedral_group) can be concisely written as:

${\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\mathrm {r} _{j}\,\mathrm {r} _{k}&=\mathrm {r} _{(j+k){\text{ mod }}n}\\\mathrm {r} _{j}\,\mathrm {s} _{k}&=\mathrm {s} _{(j+k){\text{ mod }}n}\\\mathrm {s} _{j}\,\mathrm {r} _{k}&=\mathrm {s} _{(j-k){\text{ mod }}n}\\\mathrm {s} _{j}\,\mathrm {s} _{k}&=\mathrm {r} _{(j-k){\text{ mod }}n}\end{aligned}}}$

These rules, as noted previously, are simply a more formal expression of the [composition](/Composition_of_functions) table, ensuring that all operations are performed using [modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic) modulo $n$. (For further context, one might compare these operations to the broader topic of [coordinate rotations and reflections](/Coordinate_rotations_and_reflections).)

For the specific case of the [dihedral group D 2](/Dihedral_group), it is generated by a [rotation](/Rotation) $r$ of 180 degrees and a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) $s$ across the $x$-axis. The elements of [D 2](/Dihedral_group) can then be enumerated as $\{e, r, s, rs\}$, where $e$ is the [identity](/Identity_element) or null transformation, and $rs$ represents a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) across the $y$-axis.

| The four elements of D 2 (x-axis is vertical here) |
|---|
| |

As previously mentioned, [D 2](/Dihedral_group) is [isomorphic](/Group_isomorphism) to the [Klein four-group](/Klein_four-group), a small but significant [abelian group](/Abelian_group).

It is for $n > 2$ that the operations of [rotation](/Rotation) and [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) generally cease to [commute](/Commutative), rendering [D n](/Dihedral_group) a non-[abelian group](/Abelian_group). Take [D 4](/Dihedral_group) as a prime example: a 90-degree [rotation](/Rotation) followed by a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) yields a distinctly different result than a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) followed by that same 90-degree [rotation](/Rotation). The order of operations, in these cases, is not merely a suggestion; it's a fundamental determinant of the outcome.

| D 4 is nonabelian (x-axis is vertical here). |
|---|
| |

Thus, beyond their rather obvious utility in analyzing [symmetry](/Symmetry) problems within the plane, these groups serve a crucial pedagogical role. They are among the simplest, most accessible examples of non-[abelian groups](/Abelian_group), and as such, they frequently appear as convenient counterexamples to theorems that, unfortunately for some, are exclusively restricted to [abelian groups](/Abelian_group). They quickly disabuse one of the notion that all groups behave as nicely as the [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group) or the [integers](/Integer) under addition.

The $2n$ distinct elements of [D n](/Dihedral_group) can be systematically listed as $e, r, r^2, \ldots, r^{n-1}$ for the [rotations](/Rotation), and $s, rs, r^2s, \ldots, r^{n-1}s$ for the [axis-reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)). It's worth noting that all these [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) elements inherently have an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of 2, meaning applying them twice returns the object to its original state. A simple rule of thumb for [composition](/Composition_of_functions) is this: the product of two [rotations](/Rotation) or two [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) will always result in a [rotation](/Rotation). Conversely, the product of a [rotation](/Rotation) and a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) will invariably yield another [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)).

Up to this point, our discussion of [D n](/Dihedral_group) has primarily positioned it as a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of [O(2)](/Orthogonal_group), which is the [group](/Group_(mathematics)) encompassing all [rotations](/Rotation) (about the origin) and [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) (across axes through the origin) of the plane. However, the notation [D n](/Dihedral_group) also extends to denote a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of [SO(3)](/SO(3)) that also possesses the abstract group type [D n](/Dihedral_group). This refers to the [proper symmetry group](/Symmetry_group) of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) when it is considered as an object embedded in three-dimensional space (assuming $n \geq 3$). Such a geometric figure can be conceptualized as a degenerate regular solid, one where its faces are counted twice. This peculiar characteristic is precisely why it is also termed a *dihedron* (derived from Greek, meaning "solid with two faces"), which, in turn, provides the etymological root for the "dihedral group." This naming convention follows the pattern of other well-known symmetry groups, such as the [tetrahedral](/Tetrahedron), [octahedral](/Octahedron), and [icosahedral group](/Icosahedron), which respectively refer to the proper [symmetry groups](/Symmetry_group) of a regular [tetrahedron](/Tetrahedron), [octahedron](/Octahedron), and [icosahedron](/Icosahedron).

