### Properties

The universe, it seems, has a preference for parity, and the [properties](/Dihedral_group#Properties) of the [dihedral groups D n](/Dihedral_group) with $n \geq 3$ are no exception. Their characteristics often hinge on whether $n$ is an even or an odd number. For instance, the [center](/Center_of_a_group) of [D n](/Dihedral_group) — that collection of elements that [commute](/Commutativity) with every other element in the group — consists solely of the [identity element](/Identity_element) if $n$ is odd. A rather sparse center, one might say. However, if $n$ is even, the center expands to include two elements: the [identity](/Identity_element) itself and the element ${\displaystyle r^{n/2}}$. When viewed as a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of [O(2)](/Orthogonal_group), this ${\displaystyle r^{n/2}}$ corresponds to [inversion](/Inversion_(discrete_mathematics)), a rotation by 180 degrees. Since [scalar multiplication](/Scalar_multiplication) by $-1$ inherently [commutes](/Commutativity) with any [linear transformation](/Linear_map), it's perfectly clear why this element finds its way into the center of the group.

In the context of 2D [isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry), the presence of this additional element in the center for even $n$ means effectively adding [inversion](/Inversion_(discrete_mathematics)) to the group. This operation generates new [rotations](/Rotation) and [mirrors](/Reflection_(mathematics)) that are precisely positioned between the existing ones, creating a richer set of [symmetries](/Symmetry).

More generally, if $m$ is a [divisor](/Divisor) of $n$, then [D n](/Dihedral_group) will contain precisely $n/m$ [subgroups](/Subgroup) that are themselves of type [D m](/Dihedral_group). Additionally, it will possess one [subgroup](/Subgroup) isomorphic to the [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group) ${\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} _{m}}$. Consequently, the total number of [subgroups](/Subgroup) within [D n](/Dihedral_group) (for $n \geq 1$) can be calculated as ${\displaystyle d(n) + \sigma(n)}$, where $d(n)$ represents the number of positive [divisors](/Divisor) of $n$, and ${\displaystyle \sigma(n)}$ is the sum of those positive [divisors](/Divisor) of $n$. For a more concrete illustration, one can consult a [list of small groups](/List_of_small_groups) for cases where $n \leq 8$.

The [dihedral group of order 8](/Dihedral_group_of_order_8) (D 4 ) holds a particular distinction: it is the smallest example of a group that defies classification as a [T-group](/T-group_(mathematics)). A [T-group](/T-group_(mathematics)) is one where all [subnormal subgroups](/Normal_subgroup) are normal. In D 4, while its two [Klein four-group](/Klein_four-group) [subgroups](/Subgroup) are themselves normal within D 4 , they each contain order-2 [subgroups](/Subgroup) (generated by a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics), or "flip")) that are normal within the [Klein four-group](/Klein_four-group) but are *not* normal within the larger D 4 . This intricate structure makes D 4 a useful counterexample in advanced [group theory](/Group_theory).

#### Conjugacy classes of reflections

The behavior of [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) within [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) also exhibits a dependence on the parity of $n$. All [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) are [conjugate](/Conjugacy_class) to one another if and only if $n$ is odd. This means that for an odd $n$, any [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) can be transformed into any other [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) by conjugation with some element of the group. However, if $n$ is even, the [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) neatly partition into two distinct [conjugacy classes](/Conjugacy_class).

Geometrically, this distinction is quite vivid when considering the [isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry) of a [regular $n$-gon](/Regular_polygon): for an odd $n$, the group's [rotations](/Rotation) are sufficient to move any mirror axis to any other mirror axis, as every axis passes through both a vertex and the midpoint of an opposite side. But for an even $n$, the situation is different. Only half of the mirror axes can be reached from a given mirror by [rotations](/Rotation) within the group. The even polygon explicitly displays two sets of axes: those that pass through pairs of opposite vertices, and those that pass through the midpoints of pairs of opposite sides. Each of these sets forms its own [conjugacy class](/Conjugacy_class).

From an algebraic perspective, this phenomenon for odd $n$ is a direct consequence of the [conjugate Sylow theorem](/Sylow_theorem). When $n$ is odd, each [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)), combined with the [identity](/Identity_element), forms a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of [order](/Order_(group_theory)) 2. This [subgroup](/Subgroup) is a [Sylow 2-subgroup](/Sylow_subgroup), since 2 (which is $2^1$) is the highest power of 2 that divides the group's order, $2n$ (where $n$ is odd, so $2n = 2 \times (\text{odd number})$). Conversely, when $n$ is even, these order-2 [subgroups](/Subgroup) generated by [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) are *not* [Sylow subgroups](/Sylow_subgroup), because 4 (a higher power of 2) divides the group's order (since $n$ is even, $2n$ is divisible by 4).

For $n$ even, a fascinating consequence arises: there exists an [outer automorphism](/Outer_automorphism) that explicitly interchanges these two types of [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)). More precisely, it's a class of [outer automorphisms](/Outer_automorphism), all of which are [conjugate](/Conjugacy_class) to each other by an [inner automorphism](/Inner_automorphism). This [outer automorphism](/Outer_automorphism) can be conceptualized as a [rotation](/Rotation) by ${\displaystyle \pi/n}$ (half the minimal rotation angle), an operation that is not part of the original [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) but reveals its deeper structural connections.

### Automorphism group

The [automorphism group](/Automorphism_group) of [D n](/Dihedral_group) is remarkably [isomorphic](/Isomorphic) to the [holomorph](/Holomorph_(mathematics)) of ${\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} }$. This means it is isomorphic to Hol(${\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} }$) = $\{ax + b \mid (a,n)=1\}$, and its [order](/Order_(group_theory)) is given by $n\phi(n)$, where $\phi$ is [Euler's totient function](/Totient). The totient function, for those needing a refresher, counts the number of positive integers less than or equal to $n$ that are [coprime](/Coprime) to $n$.

Understanding the structure of the [automorphism group](/Automorphism_group) can be approached by considering the actions on the group's generators: a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) and an elementary [rotation](/Rotation) (specifically, a [rotation](/Rotation) by $k(2\pi/n)$, where $k$ is [coprime](/Coprime) to $n$). Whether these [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group) are [inner](/Inner_automorphism) or [outer](/Outer_automorphism) depends critically on the parity of $n$.

*   For $n$ odd, the [dihedral group](/Dihedral_group) is [centerless](/Center_of_a_group), meaning only the [identity element](/Identity_element) [commutes](/Commutativity) with all other elements. Consequently, every non-identity element defines a non-trivial [inner automorphism](/Inner_automorphism).
*   For $n$ even, however (with the exception of $n=2$), the [rotation](/Rotation) by 180° (which corresponds to a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) through the origin) constitutes the non-trivial element within the group's [center](/Center_of_a_group).

Based on this, we can further refine the understanding of the [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism):

*   When $n$ is odd, the [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism) has an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of $2n$.
*   When $n$ is even (and not equal to 2), the [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism) has an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of $n$.

Revisiting the [conjugacy classes](/Conjugacy_class) of [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)):

*   For $n$ odd, all [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) are [conjugate](/Conjugacy_class) to one another, forming a single class.
*   For $n$ even, as discussed, they split into two distinct classes (those passing through two vertices and those passing through two faces). These classes are related by an [outer automorphism](/Outer_automorphism), which can be visualized as a [rotation](/Rotation) by $\pi/n$ (half the minimal rotation angle).

The [rotations](/Rotation) within [D n](/Dihedral_group) form a [normal subgroup](/Normal_subgroup). Conjugation by a [reflection](/Reflection_(mathematics)) has the effect of changing the sign (or direction) of the [rotation](/Rotation), while otherwise leaving its magnitude unchanged. Therefore, any [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group) that multiply the angles of [rotation](/Rotation) by some factor $k$ (where $k$ is [coprime](/Coprime) to $n$) are considered [outer automorphisms](/Outer_automorphism), unless $k = \pm 1$.

#### Examples of automorphism groups

Let's consider a few concrete examples, as they tend to clarify matters more effectively than abstract prose:

*   **D 9**: This group possesses 18 [inner automorphisms](/Inner_automorphism). When viewed as a 2D [isometry group](/Euclidean_plane_isometry), [D 9](/Dihedral_group) is characterized by mirrors positioned at 20° intervals. These 18 [inner automorphisms](/Inner_automorphism) correspond precisely to [rotations](/Rotation) of these mirrors by multiples of 20°, along with the [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)). As an [isometry group](/Euclidean_plane_isometry), these are, in fact, all the [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group). However, as an abstract group, [D 9](/Dihedral_group) also exhibits an additional 36 [outer automorphisms](/Outer_automorphism). For instance, an operation that multiplies all angles of rotation by 2 would be an [outer automorphism](/Outer_automorphism).
*   **D 10**: This group has 10 [inner automorphisms](/Inner_automorphism). In its manifestation as a 2D [isometry group](/Euclidean_plane_isometry), [D 10](/Dihedral_group) features mirrors spaced at 18° intervals. The 10 [inner automorphisms](/Inner_automorphism) correspond to [rotations](/Rotation) of these mirrors by multiples of 36° and the [reflections](/Reflection_(mathematics)) themselves. As an [isometry group](/Euclidean_plane_isometry), there are 10 additional [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group) that are [conjugates](/Conjugacy_class) by [isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry) *outside* the group, effectively rotating the mirrors by 18° relative to the [inner automorphisms](/Inner_automorphism). As an abstract group, beyond these 10 [inner](/Inner_automorphism) and 10 [outer automorphisms](/Outer_automorphism) (as isometries), there are yet another 20 [outer automorphisms](/Outer_automorphism). An example would be multiplying [rotations](/Rotation) by 3.

To put these numbers in perspective, one might compare the values of [Euler's totient function](/Euler%27s_totient_function), $\phi(n)$, for $n=9$ and $n=10$. For $n=9$, $\phi(9)=6$. For $n=10$, $\phi(10)=4$. These values explain the observed multiplication factors in the number of [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group) when compared to the two [automorphisms](/Automorphism_group) that simply preserve or reverse the order of [rotations](/Rotation) as [isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry).

It is a rather specific, almost peculiar, fact that the only values of $n$ for which [Euler's totient function](/Euler%27s_totient_function) $\phi(n) = 2$ are $n=3, 4,$ and $6$. Consequently, this implies that there are only three [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group) that are [isomorphic](/Isomorphic) to their own [automorphism groups](/Automorphism_group): these are [D 3](/Dihedral_group) (which has an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of 6), [D 4](/Dihedral_group) (with an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of 8), and [D 6](/Dihedral_group) (with an [order](/Order_(group_theory)) of 12). A rather neat little anomaly in the grand scheme of things.

#### Inner automorphism group

The [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism) of [D n](/Dihedral_group) is, as one might expect, also dependent on the parity of $n$. It is [isomorphic](/Isomorphic) to:

*   [D n](/Dihedral_group) itself, if $n$ is odd. This means that every [automorphism](/Automorphism_group) generated by conjugation is itself an element of [D n](/Dihedral_group).
*   [D n / Z 2](/Quotient_group) if $n$ is even. For the special case of $n=2$, [D 2 / Z 2](/Quotient_group) is trivial, meaning it is the [identity group](/Trivial_group) (of order 1), which aligns with [D 2](/Dihedral_group) being [abelian](/Abelian_group) and having a trivial [inner automorphism group](/Inner_automorphism).

### Generalizations

The concept of [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group), while seemingly specific to regular polygons, provides a fertile ground for several important generalizations that extend its utility and theoretical reach:

*   The [infinite dihedral group](/Infinite_dihedral_group) stands as a direct extension, representing an [infinite group](/Infinite_group) that mirrors the algebraic structure of its finite counterparts. It can be elegantly conceptualized as the [group of symmetries](/Symmetry_group) of the [integers](/Integer) (${\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} }$), where reflections and translations take the place of finite rotations.
*   The [orthogonal group](/Orthogonal_group) [O(2)](/Orthogonal_group), which is the complete [symmetry group](/Symmetry_group) of the [circle](/Circle), shares a profound kinship with the [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group). It effectively represents the limiting case of [D n](/Dihedral_group) as $n$ approaches infinity, encompassing continuous rotations and reflections.
*   The broader family of [generalized dihedral groups](/Generalized_dihedral_group) serves as an overarching category that subsumes both the finite and infinite examples mentioned above, along with a multitude of other groups that share similar structural properties.
*   The [quasidihedral groups](/Quasidihedral_group), sometimes also referred to as modular groups, constitute another distinct family of [finite groups](/Finite_group). These groups possess properties that are remarkably similar to, yet subtly distinct from, the traditional [dihedral groups](/Dihedral_group), making them an interesting area of comparative study in [group theory](/Group_theory).

